(479, 1, '2018-05-27 20:48:44', '2018-05-27 15:18:44', 'World\'s Oldest Valentine\'s\r\nEngland and Portugal.\r\n\r\nIt\'s been six hundred and thirty one years and the love is still as fresh as it was when it all first began, smelling of daffodils and carnations; this is the paradigm of trust. Yes, they\'ve been in a pickle here and there but you know, what is togetherness without a few hiccups,anyway ?\r\n<div class=\"text_exposed_show\">\r\n\r\nAnd it all began, as usual, with friendship.\r\n\r\nIt was a Treaty of friendship and mutual support between Portugal and England, known as the \'Anglo-Portuguese Alliance\', celebrated in 1373 and signed by King Edward III of England and King Fernando I and Queen Leonor of Portugal.\r\nThe oldest political aliance between two countries as it is, still in force, was signed on the 9th of May, 1386 at Windsor and sealed by the marriage of King John I of Portugal (House of Aviz) to Philippa of Lancaster, daughter of John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster. With the victory at the Battle of Aljubarrota, assisted by English archers, John I was recognized as the undisputed King of Portugal, putting an end to the interregnum of the 1383–1385 Crisis. The Treaty of Windsor established a pact of mutual support between the countries.\r\nHistorically, the Kingdom of Portugal and the Kingdom of England, and later the modern Portugal and United Kingdom, have never waged war against each other nor have they participated in wars on opposite sides as independent states since the signing of the Treaty of Windsor. While Portugal was subsumed under the Iberian Union, rebellious Portuguese factions and government in exile sought refuge and help in England. England spearheaded the Anglo-Spanish War (1585–1604) on the side of the deposed Portuguese royal house.\r\n\r\nThe alliance has served both countries throughout their respective military histories, influencing the participation of the United Kingdom in the Iberian Peninsular War, the UK\'s major land contribution to the Napoleonic Wars and the establishment of an Anglo-American base in Portugal. Portugal aided England (and later the UK) in times of need, for example, in the First World War. Today, Portugal and the United Kingdom are both part of NATO, a larger intergovernmental military alliance between several North American and European states that accounts for over 70% of total global military spending.\r\n\r\nThis is what we call as the quintessence of international diplomacy and irrevocable trust. The world needs more of them for nations to subsist and co-exist at the same time.\r\n\r\nPhilippa of Lancaster holding a book and King João I of Portugal holding a sword\r\nLike in many tombs of couples they\'re represented holding their hands\r\n\r\n</div>', 'World\'s Oldest Valentines', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'worlds-oldest-valentines', '', '', '2018-05-27 20:48:44', '2018-05-27 15:18:44', '', 0, 'https://kiitmun.org/?p=479', 0, 'post', '', 0),
